[[File:NH-Pluto-bw-NewHorizons-20150713a.jpg|thumb|300px|LORRI captured this panchromatic greyscale image of Pluto on July 13, 2015 when still almost half a million miles away from the icy dwarf planet.]] '''Long Range Reconnaissance Imager''' ('''LORRI''') is a telescope aboard the ''[[New Horizons]]'' spacecraft for imaging.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/image/nh-lorri-instrument|title=Long Range Reconnaissance Imager (LORRI) Instrument|last=Talbert|first=Tricia|date=2015-03-26|work=NASA|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en}}</ref> LORRI has been used to image Jupiter and its moons and especially [[Pluto]] and its system of [[Moons of Pluto|moons]] since its launched in 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2015/07/the-voyage-of-new-horizons-jupiter-pluto-and-beyond/398408/|title=The Voyage of New Horizons: Jupiter, Pluto, and Beyond|last=Taylor|first=Alan|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en-US}}</ref> LORRI is a [[reflecting telescope]] of [[Ritchey–Chrétien telescope|Ritchey-Chrétien]] design, and it has a [[Primary mirror|main mirror]] diameter of 20.8 cm (8.2 inches) across.<ref name="Cheng et al 2009">{{Cite book |doi=10.1007/978-0-387-89518-5_9 |chapter=Long-Range Reconnaissance Imager on New Horizons |title=New Horizons |pages=189–215 |year=2009 |last1=Cheng |first1=A. F. |last2=Weaver |first2=H. A. |last3=Conard |first3=S. J. |last4=Morgan |first4=M. F. |last5=Barnouin-Jha |first5=O. |last6=Boldt |first6=J. D. |last7=Cooper |first7=K. A. |last8=Darlington |first8=E. H. |last9=Grey |first9=M. P. |last10=Hayes |first10=J. R. |last11=Kosakowski |first11=K. E. |last12=Magee |first12=T. |last13=Rossano |first13=E. |last14=Sampath |first14=D. |last15=Schlemm |first15=C. |last16=Taylor |first16=H. W. |isbn=978-0-387-89517-8 }}</ref><ref name="pluto.jhuapl.edu Payload">http://pluto.jhuapl.edu/Mission/Spacecraft/Payload.php{{full|date=October 2018}}</ref> Images are taken with a [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] capturing data with 1024 × 1024 [[Pixel|pixels]].<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/> LORRI is a telescopic panchromatic imager integrated with the ''New Horizons'' spacecraft, and it is one of seven major science instruments on the probe.<ref name="pluto.jhuapl.edu Payload"/> LORRI does not have any moving parts and is pointed by moving the entire ''New Horizons'' spacecraft.<ref name="pluto.jhuapl.edu Payload"/> LORRI has a narrow field of view, less than a third of one degree.<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/>
==Operations== [[File:Nh ultima thule first detection v3.jpg|thumb|right|First image of {{mp|2014 MU|69}} by ''New Horizons'', taken on 16 August 2018 with LORRI. Left: Raw image includes background stars. Right: After being processed for background star subtraction.]] LORRI was used to calculate [[albedo]]<nowiki/>s for Pluto and Charon.<ReF>{{Cite journal |arxiv = 1604.06129|bibcode = 2017Icar..287..207B|title = Global albedos of Pluto and Charon from LORRI New Horizons observations|journal = Icarus|volume = 287|pages = 207–217|last1 = Buratti|first1 = B. J.|last2 = Hofgartner|first2 = J. D.|last3 = Hicks|first3 = M. D.|last4 = Weaver|first4 = H. A.|last5 = Stern|first5 = S. A.|last6 = Momary|first6 = T.|last7 = Mosher|first7 = J. A.|last8 = Beyer|first8 = R. A.|last9 = Verbiscer|first9 = A. J.|last10 = Zangari|first10 = A. M.|last11 = Young|first11 = L. A.|last12 = Lisse|first12 = C. M.|last13 = Singer|first13 = K.|last14 = Cheng|first14 = A.|last15 = Grundy|first15 = W.|last16 = Ennico|first16 = K.|last17 = Olkin|first17 = C. B.|year = 2017|doi = 10.1016/j.icarus.2016.11.012}}</ref> LORRI is also used for navigation, especially to more precisely determine the location of a flyby target.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.astrobio.net/also-in-news/new-horizons-sets-up-for-new-years-flyby-of-ultima-thule/|title=New Horizons Sets Up for New Year's Flyby of Ultima Thule - Astrobiology Magazine|date=2018-10-09|work=Astrobiology Magazine|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2018, ''New Horizons'' spacecraft utilized navigation data from LORRI for its planned flyby of [[(486958) 2014 MU69|Ultima Thule]] ((486958) 2014 MU69) flyby target in a couple months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spaceflightinsider.com/missions/solar-system/engine-burn-puts-new-horizons-on-track-to-ultima-thule/|title=Engine burn puts New Horizons on track to Ultima Thule|date=2018-10-09|work=SpaceFlight Insider|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en-US}}</ref>
During the cruise to Jupiter, LORRI data was also used to determine a value for the cosmic optical background as an alternative to other methods.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/ncomms15003 |pmid=28397781 |pmc=5394269 |bibcode=2017NatCo...815003Z |title=Measurement of the cosmic optical background using the long range reconnaissance imager on New Horizons |journal=Nature Communications |volume=8 |pages=15003 |last1=Zemcov |first1=Michael |last2=Immel |first2=Poppy |last3=Nguyen |first3=Chi |last4=Cooray |first4=Asantha |last5=Lisse |first5=Carey M. |last6=Poppe |first6=Andrew R. |year=2017 }}</ref> At Jupiter, LORRI was used for an extensive observation campaign of Jupiter's atmosphere, rings, and moons.<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/>
On Aug. 29, 2006, the cover on LORRI was opened and it took an image in space of [[Messier 7]] (aka Ptolemy’s Cluster) for its [[First light (astronomy)|first light]] image.<ref>http://pluto.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/News-Article.php?page=090106{{full|date=October 2018}}</ref> The following year, in 2007 when it flew by Jupiter for its gravity assist, it was used to image Jupiter and its moons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pluto.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/News-Article.php?page=20100727|title=LORRI Looks Back at "Old Friend" Jupiter|last=JHUAPL|work=New Horizons|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref> LORRI also imaged the Jovian system in 2010 as part of an Annual Checkout confirming the operation of LORRI, taking pictures from a distance of about 16 AU. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pluto.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/News-Article.php?page=20100727|title=LORRI Looks Back at "Old Friend" Jupiter|last=JHUAPL|work=New Horizons|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref>
In 2015, LORRI was used to take extensive imaging of Pluto before and during the flyby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pluto.jhuapl.edu/Mission/The-Flyby.php|title=New Horizons|website=pluto.jhuapl.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref>
In August 2018, LORRI was able to visually detect 2014 MU69 'Ultima Thule' at distance of about 100 million miles (about 1 AU or 161 million km).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pluto.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/News-Article.php?page=20180828|title=Ultima in View|last=JHUAPL|work=New Horizons|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref>
==Specifications== [[File:New Horizons LORRI.jpg|thumb|LORRI being installed in the spacecraft in 2004.<reF>{{cite web | url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/newhorizons/multimedia/lorri.html | title=NASA - LORRI Instrument}}</ref>]] {| class=wikitable style="text-align:center; float:right; margin:10px" |- | colspan="8" style="text-align:center;"|'''Examples''' |- ! Name !! Wavelength Bandpass || Aperture |- | Human eye || 400–700 nm (approx.)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/the-visible-light-spectrum-2699036|title=What Is the Visible Light Spectrum?|work=ThoughtCo|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref>|| 0.6 cm<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.popphoto.com/news/2012/06/how-to-calculate-f-stop-human-eye|title=How to Calculate the F-stop of the Human Eye|work=Popular Photography|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref> |- | LORRI || 350 – 850 nm || 20.8 cm |- |} LORRi is a reflecting telescope integrated with the unmanned ''New Horizons'' spacecraft, it can take black and white digital pictures of astronomical targets.<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/>
Specifications:<ref name="pluto.jhuapl.edu Payload"/><ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/><ref name="pluto.jhuapl.edu Payload"/> *Telescope style: Ritchey-Chrétien *Primary mirror diameter: 20.8 cm (8.2 inches) **Mirror substance: [[Silicon Carbide]] *Focal length 263 cm (103.5 inches)<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/> *Mass: 8.8 kilograms (19.4 pounds) *Average electrical power use: 5.8 [[Watt|watts]] *Field of View: 0.29 degrees *Resolution: 4.95 μrad pixels<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/> *Bandpass: from about 350 nm to 850 nm<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/> *Operating temperature: 148K to 313K<ref name="Robichaud et al 2008">{{cite journal |bibcode=2008amos.confE..67R |title=Silicon Carbide Optics for Space Situational Awareness and Responsive Space Needs |journal=Advanced Maui Optical and Space Surveillance Technologies Conference |pages=E67 |last1=Robichaud |first1=J. |last2=Green |first2=J. |last3=Catropa |first3=D. |last4=Rider |first4=B. |last5=Ullathorne |first5=C. |year=2008 }}</ref>
The mirror is made of the material silicon carbide which helped support meeting the thermal requirements of the design.<ref name="Robichaud et al 2008"/>
The detector is a thinned [[Back-illuminated sensor|backside-illuminated]] charge-coupled device, and records 1024 by 1024 pixels, with a variety of exposure settings.<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/> LORRI can take one picture per second and store the picture digitally as a 12-bit image, with either lossless or [[lossy compression]].<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/> (See also [[Data compression]])
LORRI incorporates a [[Field flattener lens|field-flattening lens]], with three elements.<ReF>[https://arxiv.org/ftp/arxiv/papers/0709/0709.4278.pdf]</reF>
The design can take images at very light low levels required for the mission, including light levels 1/900 those of Earth when it is at Pluto.<ref name="Cheng et al 2009"/> For the 2014 MU69 encounter, the longest exposure time, which was up to ten seconds for the Pluto flyby was increased.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2018/0124-new-horizons-prepares-for-2014mu69.html|title=New Horizons prepares for encounter with 2014 MU69|website=www.planetary.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> This was accomplished after the Pluto flyby by the team, to support taking images in even lower light levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2018/0124-new-horizons-prepares-for-2014mu69.html|title=New Horizons prepares for encounter with 2014 MU69|website=www.planetary.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>
After the Pluto times, exposure times of at least 30 seconds were made possible (half a minute), which was also useful for doing reconnaissance images and enabling imaging down to 21 magnitude.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2018/0124-new-horizons-prepares-for-2014mu69.html|title=New Horizons prepares for encounter with 2014 MU69|website=www.planetary.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> [[Magnitude (astronomy)|Magnitude]] in astronomy is way to measure brightness, and higher number is dimmer; two related concepts are [[Apparent magnitude]] and [[Absolute magnitude]].
LORRI is pointed by moving the entire spacecraft, which limits the exposure time.<ref name="pluto.jhuapl.edu Payload"/><ReF>[https://arxiv.org/ftp/arxiv/papers/0709/0709.4278.pdf]</ref> The spacecraft does not have reaction wheels and is stabilized by [[Thrusters (spacecraft)|thrusters]].<reF>[https://arxiv.org/ftp/arxiv/papers/0709/0709.4278.pdf]</reF>
==Jovian system== While passing by Jupiter in February 2017, the Jovian system was observed using LORRI and other instruments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pluto.jhuapl.edu/Mission/The-Path-to-Pluto/Jupiter-Encounter.php|title=New Horizons|website=pluto.jhuapl.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref>
