[[File:Flickr - The U.S. Army - Three is a crowd.jpg|U.S. soldiers wearing New Year's glasses for 2009.|right|thumb]]'''New Year's glasses''' are [[novelty item|novelty]] [[Glasses|eyeglasses]] in the numerical shape of the coming year usually worn during [[New Year's Eve]] parties.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lawson|first=Richard|title=The Sad Ending of the 200_ New Year’s Glasses|url=http://gawker.com/5121460/the-sad-ending-of-the-200_-new-years-glasses|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101095822/http://gawker.com/5121460/the-sad-ending-of-the-200_-new-years-glasses|dead-url=yes|archive-date=1 January 2009|work=Gawker.com|accessdate=22 February 2012|df=}}</ref> They were invented and [[Patent|patented]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Barkai|first=R.|title=Novelty eyeglass frames  Richard E. Sclafani et al|url=http://www.google.ca/patents?id=nawqAAAAEBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Richard+Sclafani&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-xRFT6yuNoiv0AGX8IGrBA&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAA|work=Google Patents|publisher=United States Patent Office|accessdate=22 February 2012}}</ref>  by Richard Sclafani and Peter Cicero in 1990, although other companies have produced similar versions.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lacitis|first=Erik|title=As 2008 closes, so does business for those year-end glasses|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2008575545_glasses31m.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090117021151/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2008575545_glasses31m.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=17 January 2009|work=Seattle Times|publisher=The Seattle Times Company|accessdate=22 February 2012|df=}}</ref> New Year's glasses' inspiration and popularity arose from the fact that the two digits in the middle of the year number (9 and 0 from the years 1990-2009) had holes suitable for looking through or mounting lenses into.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lefkowitz|first=Melanie|title=Glasses for New Year's Eve Parties - 2011 Still Works|url=http://main.stylelist.com/2010/12/28/2011-glasses-new-year-s/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321193545/http://main.stylelist.com/2010/12/28/2011-glasses-new-year-s|dead-url=yes|archive-date=21 March 2013|work=Stylist|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=22 February 2012|df=}}</ref>

==Availability==

New Year's Glasses are often sold at New Year's Eve events and parties. [[Hawker (trade)|Street vendors]] in [[New York City|NYC]] are known to sell the glasses with extremely high markups. In 2015, the average cost of glasses in [[Times Square]] was upwards of $25.{{fact|date=February 2017}}

==Safety==

New Year's glasses can restrict vision due to the large frame. The large frame can also cause discomfort.{{fact|date=February 2017}}

